1. Kube Config file
How to use kube control command to specifically use kube config file.

Kube config file define 3 section - clusters, context, users. 

Cluster: It has Certificate authority info ca.crt and name of the cluster (mykube-prod)
Users: Admin user will have info like admin.crt & admin.key and name of the user (myuser-admin)
Context: It will link the user with the cluster myuser-admin@mykube-prod

Cluster:
Production - mykube-prod
Stage - mykube-stage
Developement - mykube-dev

Users:
Admin - myuser-admin
Developers - myuser-dev
Devops - myuser-devops

Context:
mykube-prod@myuser-admin
mykube-stage@myuser-dev

Also context can mention the namespace of the cluster.

Basically kubeconfig file will have the info like which user can access to which cluster with the certificate validation and verification and
user-cluster are linked with the context.

if kubeconfig.yml is defined in the default path Home /.kube/config then kubectl command can be used directly

# kubectl config view  (it will show all the info in the kubeconfig)
# kubectl config set-context (name of the context)
# kubectl config use-context
# kubectl config view
# kubectl config --kubeconfig=/root/ set-context (name of the context) ((specific path))

Note: Instead of mentioning the ca.crt in the kubeconfig file of cluster info, try to mention the path /etc/kubernets/pki/ca.crt or add the
encrypted certificate in it.


