3. Authorization
Once the authentication is applied for the user. Authorization is will be followed to do their mechanism. So, what they can do with the 
authorization.

Node Authorizer: User try to connect kube-apiserver or kubelet will access kube-apiserver. With the node authorizer - control the access
                 to the user or the components in the cluster.
ABAC: Attribute based access control - user1 can access the policy1 and user2 access the policy2. Each policy define the access control.
      Whenever the new access to be added in the existing policy then we need to restart kube-apiserver. This is not recommneded         
RBAC: Role based access control - role1 and role2 will be created with set of actions like create, delete, get pods.
      Now user will be mapped to the role1 and in the future new actions will be added in the role object.
WebHook: Third party tool will do the authorization, it allows the user to access the kube-apiserver with the rule/policy defined in it.
AlwaysAllow: By default alwaysallow is configured in the kube-apiserver service configuration. Won't do any authorization.
AlwaysDeny: It will deny all the request from the user or bots.....



