        # kubectl create -f developer-role.yaml
Step 2: Create a rolebinding with the username and role object name details
        # kubectl create -f developer-rolebinding.yaml

Step 3: # kubectl get roles
        # kubectl get rolebinding

Checking Access
Step 4: # kubectl auth can-i create pods
        # kubectl auth can-i delete nodes
        # kubectl auth can-i get nodes as dev-user -namespace research

Note: Also we can mention namespace to restrict the user. And the pod info in the role.yml to restrict the pod from the user to get 
      the details.

5. Cluster Roles and Cluster Role Binding: Cluster Scoped
Cluster role is used to create it to access the cluster scoped resources like Node, pvc, certificatesigningrequest, clusterroles, clusterrolebinding

cluster-admin-user - can view nodes, delete nodes, create nodes.....

Cluster Role: It is created a role (cluster-administrative-role) with access to list, create, delete nodes.
Cluster Role Binding: cluster-admin-user will be mapped with role reference od cluster-adminisstrative

Note: If a user got a access to the node then he can access all the namespaces in the node.
Role & Rolebinding is helpful for specific namespace.


6. Service Account:
A service account is used for the other applications or services to interact with kubernetes.
Token in the service account is used to prove his identity.
To create service account # kubectl create serviceaccount dashboard-k8s (serviceaccountname)
To create a Token in the service account which is used by the other applications # kubectl create token dashboard-k8s --duration 2h

Every namespace has a default service account.
The default serviceaccount is automatically attached to the pod on creation.
The newly created serviceaccount can attach to the pod by adding the "serviceaccountfield" in the pod.

Whenever serviceaccount is added to the pod: 
It automatially creates a token and mount as a volume.
Rotates the token.
It automattically expires the token when the pod is deleted.


