8. Security Context:
Docker level security context:
Basically docker will share the Host OS kernel but Container in the different namespace. Host will be in the different namesapce

If we run a container with root user, we can see the same user in the host level as root user.
But the process id will be diffrent from each other.
# docker run user=1000 nginx

list the processess from docker container namespace
# ps aux (in the container)
user PID Command
root  1  sleep 3600


list the processess from host namespace
# ps aux (in the host)
user  PID Command
root  100 sleep 3600
root  200 -bash

Note: 
Need to change the root user to non-root to restrict the access level in the docker conatiner.

Similarly we have to retrict the access to the user in the Pod level, it will restirct to all the pods.
Otherwise we can restrict it to specific container.
Capabilities like giving access to the user to controll all the control in the pod.

The User ID defined in the securityContext of the container overrides the User ID in the POD.

Restrict it in pod level:
spec:
  SecurityContext:
    runasuser: root
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: private-registry.io/apps/internal-app
  


Restrict it in container level:
spec:
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: private-registry.io/apps/internal-app
    SecurityContext:
     runasuser: 1000
    Capabilities:
      add: [mac_admin]
































